Data Exploration, GoBike - San Francisco Bay¶

by Petar Janosevic¶

Introduction¶

Today I'm going to analyze a dataset of a bike-sharing company which includes the duration of riding the bike, some informations about the bike user, start and end stations. The location is the San Francisco Bay area.

Based on these two DataFrames I assume following:

  • Stations and ID have the similar amount of missing values. I would say that the reason for this is that bike users did fetch nor return the bike at a station. I will go and check if there are duplicate longitudes in rows with missing values in stations and ID.
  • Missing values in Birthday and gender happens to subscribers and costumers. If I plan to work with that I might have to delete these rows in that particular visualization. I can leave the rows in other charts.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

Bike has 183'412 rows and 16 columns. Everything is an object or a float except the bike_id and duration_sec which are ints and which I have to convert into a string and a float. Depending on what I need to answer, I might have to change more things or nothing at all, which I doubt that I will be nothing :D.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm interested in finding out more about the company's biker-users. Are there more women, men or others? Is there something to compare between costumers and subscribers - like who is using it more and longer? I would also like to dig into the duration and when do people tend to rent the bycles? Maybe I can find out if I have more users going to work with their bike than using it for their spare time.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

There are a lot of features which can help me answer my questions. Start end Endtime, combined with the duration time for example is the most valuable column. This can help me find out when are most of the people using the bikes. The provider might have to make sure to have enough bikes and certain times. Of course I need the user type, member birthday and member gender columns as well.

We found out that the chart is unimodal. It's right skewed and the mean lies near 700 which means that people tend to rent the bike for circa 12 minutes. I don't believe that people can do 'sports' in just 12 minutes. Sporty people would have to use it for a way longer time than 12 minutes. 12 Minutes sound for me like going from place A to B fastly. I could try to find out if bycicles get rent more on the weekends than during the week. On the weekends most people tend to have days of. I'm not one of them for sure. For this I got to convert the date strings into datatime objects and create new columns day, month and year.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

I've found out a lot of things like:

  • The peak amount of rentals are in rush hour periods - in the morning and evening. This indicates that most people use our bikes to go to work or school. This statement gets stronger when we look at the day and duration_sec distribution. Both weekend days have less rentals compared to weekdays and the mean duration is around 12 minutes. I don't think that you can do sports in just 12 minutes. Looking at these charts makes me believe that most people use it for as I already stated, going to work, school or something similar.
  • We have way more male customers than we have female and others.
  • There are more subscribers than costumer amount of rentals.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

  • I needed to convert the date columns into datetime columns such that I could create new columns for the week days etc.
  • User Type column had to be converted into categoricals. I need that to compare them better later in charts.
  • I've realised that we have a couple of 'night' users. I came to that observation by comparing the durations in sec. There were some long durations in my observation and I was wondering why. That's why I compared months etc. I want to see if I can find out more about it, but maybe there are just some people who forgot to check out their bikes when they arrived home.

Bivariate Exploration¶

Conclusions¶

I wanted to find out more about the company's customers. I assume most people do this task to just analyze when bike get rent the most, who rents it etc. This is indeed something I analyzed as well, but in my opinion you always need a target why you're doing it. A company needs data analysis to improve themselves, to get more revenue and to generate more customers. That's why I tried to find out the company's heartbeat. My first intuition were the commuters, because you use a bike either for commuting, doing sport, riding in the nature and things like these. For that I looked at the mean duration and how often a bike was rent, which days had what mean and rental distribution. Finding out that the mean was about 12 minutes was a big indicator for commuting. During the week more bike were rent but on the weekend the mean was higher. My explanation for this is, that there is less data, less rentals on weekends and most people don't have to go to work or school on weekends. So if you use a bike on weekends, it's mostly for your spare time. Of course you might commute somewhere as well like going to a friend or maybe you are one of these people like me who have to work everyday, but most people have days of. That's why the mean is higher. I analyzed the rental distribution per hour and there were two peeks, one in the morning and one in the evening which are most like to be rush hour periods. At these period people go to work or go home from work which is another indicator pro the commuter argument. When I want to find out if I only have commuters, it is also important to separate the customers and subscribers. Customers tend to rent a bike longer, because they barely use it anyways. So if they rent a bike, they will most likely use it for a longer duration because the entrance price of most bikes wouldn't make up for it. I don't want to generalize that and it's very important for me to state that this is not a generalization. It's my intuition because I know the prices in Europe. I rented bikes as well but if I was a regular user, a commuter, I would never ever rent a bike for 12 minutes. I'd rather get a taxi, depending on the country and the prices. During my exploration I've realized that I need to categorize by age as well. Going to work/school people are not really known to be retired. After age stage seperation there were enough things to analyze. Looking at the mean of subscribers from different angles and different variables like gender or age stage, really strengthen my intuition that most people rent bikes for commuting.

Things to consider¶

  • Customers are a one time thing or a hobby kind of thing. It's going to be hard to convince customers to be a subscriber if they only use it for their spare time. The company might consider marketing strategies like some nature trip advises and advertising nature trips to generate more customers which could get comfortable with the company and bikes. If someone tried out the bikes and gets comfortable with them, they might consider to use it more often. Just get people to use it once to see that the company is cool.
  • Most people are commuters. Make sure that there are always enough bikes during that period of time. This is the most important time since most people use them.
  • Way more men use bikes. Think about how you can attract women to use bikes. I know that in the US most people do what stars do, unlike Switzerland. Maybe colaborate with female actress, singers or influencers.
  • The company has a very loyal pool of elderly subscribers. You might consider a body health campagne to show how healthy bikes are. I mean actual old people love your bikes and they have to be in a phenomenal shape to be able to still ride them.
  • I had to get rid of some rows. This doesn't limit my findings very much but it's still something, because we talk about a company and business. There are too many empty values for subscribers and customers. Reveiling their Birthday and Gender is nowadays not a big deal anymore. Think about making people type in their Birthday and Gender for better decisions. Except you want to start a marketing strategy based on how you don't care about personal data. This would be an exceptional and unique thing.
